               The sum of the dollar abnormal volumes over the 10‐day intervention period has a cross‐sectional correlation of 1.0 with the dollar intervention in each stock. This correlation may reflect a firm size effect captured by both variables. When both the volume variables are normalized by July market value to remove the firm size effect, the correlation is 0.94 and is very highly significant. Thus the procedure described produces a very good estimate of the daily intervention activity and enables us to analyze the relationship between returns and intervention activity using 10 daily observations on the 33 stocks, for a total of 330 observations compared to 33 observations on reported intervention amounts.

We also test a more powerful prediction of the temporary price pressure hypothesis: namely, that the price increasefor each stockduring the event period is reversed over the subsequent weeks. In other words, for every Hang Seng stockiin the test sample, we run the following regression:

